{"cursor":"2175","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn Greek mythology, 'Nephele' (, from Î½Î­ÏÎ¿Ï nephos \"cloud\"; Latinized to Nubes)\nwas a cloud nymph who figured prominently in the story of Phrixus and\nHelle. [http://www.theoi.com/Text/HyginusAstronomica2.html#20 Hyginus (Mary\nGrant translation): The Ram], (Aries)\n\nGreek myth also has it that Nephele is the cloud whom Zeus created in the image\nof Hera to trick Ixion to test his integrity after displaying his lust for Hera\nduring a feast as a guest of Zeus. Ixion failed in restraining his lust for\nHera, thus fathering the Centaurs.\n\nNephele married Athamas, but he divorced her for Ino. Phrixus and Helle, the son\nand daughter of Athamas and Nephele, were hated by their stepmother, Ino. Ino\nhatched a devious plot to get rid of the twins, roasting all the town's crop\nseeds so they would not grow. The local farmers, frightened of famine, asked a\nnearby oracle for assistance. Ino bribed the men sent to the oracle to lie and\ntell the others that the oracle required the sacrifice of Phrixus. Before he was\nkilled though, Phrixus and Helle were rescued by a flying golden ram sent by\nNephele, their natural mother.\n\nPhrixus and Helle were instructed to not look down to Earth for the duration of\ntheir flight. Helle, though, did look down, and fell off the ram into the\nHellespont (which was named after her, meaning Sea of Helle) and drowned, but\nPhrixus survived all the way to Colchis, where King Aeetes took him in and\ntreated him kindly, giving Phrixus his daughter, Chalciope, in marriage. In\ngratitude, Phrixus gave the king the Golden Fleece of the ram, which Aeetes hung\nin a tree in his kingdom. The Golden Fleece would later be taken by Jason.\n","linknr":139,"url":"Nephele","recorded":1374523170,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Nephele&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Nephele&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w